title: Traditional bushing 8x15x45mm (LM8LUU) with grease traps
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Traditional 8mm bushing. Long version. With internal grease traps.

Summary: Don't use MoS2 grease for printed bushings, it's a fail. PTFE spray can oil works with PETG bushings if wiped dry after saturation. I have not tested silicon based or lithium based lubricants. I did look for graphite dry lubricant spray as a first choice but I did not find any in my vicinity so I chose PTFE spray can oil instead and as previously stated it seems to work if wiped dry after saturation.

My first attemp to grease the Y-axis I used MoS2 dark grey grease, it worked sufficient for the linear ball bearings. When I used MoS2 dark grey grease to my printed bushings it did not work at all, tried it with PLA-bushings and PETG-bushings, they all seemed to work at first, but after one day or less they started to get to snug on the rods, they got stuck and the stepper motor struggeled with resistanse to move. NO GO for MoS2 grease and printed bushings!

I printed a new batch of PETG bushings and tried them with sprayed PTFE oil (tens of thusands of PFTE balls per mm2, micro gap fillers), I used a threaded rod to grind the bushings to tolerance, moving the bushing back and forth along the threaded rod slowly rotating them both while applying pressure (using an 8mm drill bit might work better). Grind a while and the check the bushing against the bearing rod, grind a bit more etc. until satisfied with the tolerance. I found it to be sufficient if the bushing slides easy along the rod while dry, but sticking while wet with PTFE spray can oil. I grind the bushings until they just slide easy by them selves by gravity on the rods but sticks to the rod when saturated with PTFE oil. When satisfied with tolerance I saturated both the rods and the bushings with PTFE spray can oil, moved the bushings along the rods for a while and then thouroghly wiped them all dry with toilet paper, inside of bushings as well as whole of the rods. When saturated the bushings does not fall by gravity on the rods, they are sucked by viscosity to the rods, but when wiped clean they fall easy and fast along the rods!

Lesson1: MoS2 dark gray grease works with linear ball bearings if applied inside the bearings. The linear ball bearings runs quiet and smooth with MoS2 dark gray grease (quality of bearings may vary).
Lesson2: MoS2 grease does not work at all for printed bushings, neither PLA or PETG! At least not with fine tolerances between the rod and bushing.
Lesson3: PLA might be partially dissolved by MoS2 and refined oils, I don't know, but it could be why the smoothness feels ok the first day but not the next day. PETG are resistant to oils and greases, or so they say.
Lesson4: PTFE spray can oil works with PETG bushings if you saturate the inside of the bushings and on the rods with PTFE oil, move them back and forth rapidly by hand for a while and when done wipe them completely dry inside and out. Important to understand that if wet by oil (or grease) the bushings sticks to the rod by viscosity and boundary layer adhesion. Wipe everything dry using fresh toilet paper after saturated with PTFE spray can oil, remount and realign everything carefully and you should end up with a quiet linear PETG bushing heatbed. I did.

From my, trial and error, pratical experience.
/peen333

title: 120 FIlm Clip for P6*6 Pinhole Camera

description.text: This is an accessory for the P6*6 Pinhole Camera: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:157844 I discovered that film sometimes unwinds when unloading the P6*6 (doesn't appear to be brand specific). This can cause nasty light leaks from the top and bottom of the roll, ruining several negatives at the same time. I previously advocated for gluing a small block of foam onto the inside surface of the uptake spool cavity, but I find that the foam absorbs glue, becoming too stiff to allow the insertion of an empty spool when loading. This clip is inserted with the empty uptake spool (despite the pictures of a full spool). As the roll of film is used, the clip loosely holds the film snug against the spool, allowing unloading without the light leaks and fogging ( For more information, read film_clip_instructions.doc in the downloads section).

I the best luck printing these clips with one perimeter and 50% or greater infill. Print them at the same vertical resolution as your camera, to ensure that there is a positive engagement and the clip stays in place. If it should get knocked down inside the camera, it should still work. The three sizes are labeled "25"., "50", and "75" for (now) arbitrary reasons, Consider them small, medium, and large respectively. I find the smallest size ("25") works just fine. The P6*6 has a small lip inside the body of the camera that prevents the clip from rotating during use. You will want to remove the raft and clean up the bottom edge before use. If the clip is too tight on a full spool of film you risk twisting off the spade that drives the film as you wind it. I advise printing a spare winder assembly and keeping it in your kit.

description.text:
Floating Extruder (for lack of a better name.... Bob up and down extruder)

Used with a Delta printer. I use it on my Mini Kossel Printer.
Designed to use a Wade Extruder.

Allows the use of a bowden extruder setup without needing to have bends in the bowden tubing. Allows for shortest possible length feeding tube. Because the tubing stays straight, there is a reduced force needed to push plastic through the bowden tube and needs less retraction. Also the bend in the bowden tube doesn't put lateral forces on the end effector. I got annoyed when my printer needed to retracted repeatedly and kept tearing up the filament resulting in failed prints. Now I can print really fast and with great results.

Cons: Makes the printer really tall (basically doubles height)

The extruder moves up and down with the end effector which puts less forces on the end effector when printing. The elastic band adds a counter lifting force so there is very little force needed to move the extruder up and down.

Parts:
2 - lm8uu bearings
2 - 8mm rods (length determined by print height)
1 - elastic banding
1 - Wade Extruder with bowden

Printed parts:
1 - Riser
1 - Top_Riser
1 - Riser Bungee Clip 1 & 2
1 - Roller
2 - Riser Mounts

I didn't want to waste what was otherwise a pretty good Fish Fossilz print! Here's a repair kit to get you going if part of your fish turns out badly but the rest survives.

I created this clip from scratch in Autodesk Fusion 360. The clip is about 1mm longer than the piece it replaces. There should be enough to correct that distance, but I haven't had time to do it yet.

In my case I needed to print the tail as well as this clip. I Meshmixer to separate the tail from the original STL and print it. If you want to fix some other part of the fish you can certainly combine the meshes in Meshmixer but note that you may need to make the clip section more narrow to fit in the other parts of the fish! You may also need some support. Realistically you'd only do this if you were almost out of filament or as a practical experiment with Meshmixer. description.text:
I made a relatively low volume calibration shape to allow measuring how far off printed parts will wind up. I use this to adjust scaling factors to get more accurate prints - you'll want to use whatever settings you plan to print your normal parts in.
All the measurable lengths are in increments of 5mm, and you probably won't be off by more than 5mm, but here are the measurements you might want to check:
The X and Y legs should be 100mm long with widths of 10mm, and 5mm height.
The hole should be 15mm square.
The tower should be 10mm x 10mm x 25mm.
The holes are 1.5mm, but if you're over-extruding a bit, they'll be almost closed. The holes are 80mm apart.

description.text:
This version of the Skyrim Iron Helmet is altered to make it more practical to actually print full size and wear. Video game models are unfortunately not optimized for real-world wearability :)

1) The walls of the helmet have been thinned to reasonably uniform thickness. This process smoothed away the details on the interior of the helmet...but if it's being worn you won't see those details anyway.

2) The in-game model seemed to be designed for an abnormally long head, or maybe an abnormally long nose. I did some warping and scaling to get more normal proportions.

3) Added rivet details (rivets were part of colored texture but not the normals map in the original game files)

4) Cut the model into pieces to fit a makerbot-size printer, and added holes on the edges for pins to help with assembly.

*The model is sized to approximately adult L hat size. There are 2 "sizer" pieces provided, and I recommend printing them first. Put them together into a headband which should be able to go around your head, level with the eyebrows. This will tell you if you need to scale up or down. If you are going to add padding leave extra room

**The "toddler" zip folder contains the pieces scaled down to child head size, and scaled slightly front-to-back to fit a rounder head shape.

If you are printing in pieces, use the edge holes and pegs to aid assembly. Depending on how clean your print comes out it may be helpful to use a 3mm drillbit to clean out the holes.

I recommend printing the peg file at a couple different sizes (90%, 95%, 100%, 105%) to find a snug fit. The holes are 3mm, so you could also cut pieces of 3mm filament.

I used CA glue to assemble. This worked OK but the joints were brittle--may try a different glue next time.

description.text:
This is an LED light for a disc golf basket. I created this so that I can play disc golf at night. We put this light on the basket and then we tape an LED to a coin cell battery and place it on the top of our discs. That way, we can track where our discs are as well.

The LED light is composed of 12 LEDs. Every set of three is wired in series to a 9v source (6 AAA batteries). The four sets of three are wired in parallel with each other. The LEDs wired in series were connected by drilling holes through the LED ring and twisting the leads together. Add solder for a more secure connection. The cover is used to hide all of the wire connections.

Ceramic magnets were glued in to the LED ring and a neodymium magnet was used to keep the battery pack on the steel basket.

Because it is pretty dark out there, it doesn't take much light to see the basket (though the pictures don't come out very well). However, you can add another 3 AAA batteries (12V Total) for increased luminosity.

title: Underside Mounting Bracket for Monoprice Maker Select v2 (Wanhao Duplicator i3)

description.text:
I did some quick, non-exhaustive searches on here and I didn't find any brackets to mount the cpu tower main control head to the underside of a platform or table.

I have my printer on a small 24" x 24" table from Wally World and there's a fight for space. Butted up against each other on the sides, I still get about a 1.5-2" overhang. This isn't a big deal and doesn't affect printing but why have a printer if you're not going to make stuff, right?

These are some extremely basic mounting brackets. Just print one of each (or you can print dozens and go crazy making a special cubby if you so choose). The U-shaped one should be mounted about 3/4 of the way towards the front (closer to the interface) and the Z-shaped one is for the rear.

I am currently selling these for $18,530 USD a piece or for free, whichever is easier. The former would be nice. You can also pay in yachts or small islands in which ownership can be legally and permanently transferred to me, naming me Captain or King (but not Captain King because that sounds like a terrible dictator that commanded commissioned a line of comics and movies to be written in which he is the star, hero, and, of course, Captain King).

I do all my own modeling (not that kind, dude), so if you have a request or modification idea, please let me know and I'll do my best.

*None of that Kenny G crap because this isn't 1998.

Hardware

On the original design, I used self-tapping pan head screws. The design allows for a head diameter =<6mm with a shank major diameter =<4mm.

Depending on thread density (read pitch) and thread depth, a screw with a major diameter slightly above 4mm could be used without compromising the integrity of the build. I wouldn't go more than 5% at most.

Any type of bolt should work, as long as the head is round and there isn't a taper between the bottomside of the head where it meets the shank. Many screws (e.g. drywall and wood) have that particular feature so they can be countersunk.

The pilot hole and flush mortise are stepped but I have added another set of brackets that will allow for tapered necks on the screws.

After the success of my first printable extruder design (the Printruder, see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:958 ), I wondered, if there would be an even simpler and better design for a Printruder. This is what I came up with. Please note, that there are two flavors of the main part ("Motor Block"):
  • Motorblock_v7_TimerBeltPulley.stl
    This design is for use with the standard timer belt pulley, which comes with the MakerBot Extruder MK3/MK4.
  • Motorblock_v7_WormGearPulley.stl
    This design is for use with a 10mm worm-gear style pulley
    • You only need one of both. Be sure to print the correct one! The PCB holder parts are optional. There's a post on my blog on this with more detailed information and step-by-step build instructions:
    http://pleasantsoftware.com/developer/3d/2010/03/08/printruder-ii/ In order to mount the Printruder II in a MakerBot, you might want to print also a pair of Printable Extruder Holders: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1912

• print one of the both Motor Block parts
  • print the Idler Block part
  • (Optional) Print the PCB holder parts
  • Follow the step-by-step instructions at http://pleasantsoftware.com/developer/3d/2010/03/08/printruder-ii/ to assemble the whole thing.

description.text:
This is a belt tension system for the Kossel 2020. My kossel had some really bad slop on the prints because the belts did not have the proper tension, so I decided to design these parts to solve the problem. They use an M3 screw and nut to add or remove tension from the belts. The belt is supposed to be looped through the small hole and then zip-tied to itself. These are small but really strong.
